<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>9 SPEED AND 10 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS EATON 16709 AND 16710 SERIES - REMOVE - COUNTERSHAFT BEARINGS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="9">
        <title>COUNTERSHAFT BEARINGS</title>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>In the following instructions, the front and rear bearings from BOTH countershafts are removed.
                    For removal of the mainshaft assembly from the case, it is necessary to remove the bearings from the
                    right countershaft ONLY.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the snap ring from each countershaft rear groove (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302153">Figure 53</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302153" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302153" filename="../figg13/G1302153.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 53. Remove Snap Ring</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">From inside the case, use a soft bar and maul to drive the countershaft rear bearings to the
                rear and from the case bores (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302154">Figure 54</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302154" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302154" filename="../figg13/G1302154.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 54. Drive Countershaft Rear Bearings To Rear</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>This procedure will damage the bearings and should not be attempted unless replacement of the
                        bearings is planned.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the bolt (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302155">left, Figure 55</hotlnk>) and front bearing retainer plate from the
                countershaft (right).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302155" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302155" filename="../figg13/G1302155.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 55. Front Bearing Retainer Plate</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a soft bar and maul to drive each countershaft to the rear as far as possible (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302156">Figure 56</hotlnk>). This will partially unseat the front bearings.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302156" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302156" filename="../figg13/G1302156.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 56. Countershaft To The Rear</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The soft bar used should have a flattened end that is large enough so as not to damage holes
                        for the roll pin and bolt.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">From the case rear, use a soft bar and maul to drive each countershaft forward to unseat the
                front bearings from the case bores and expose the bearing snap rings (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302157">Figure 57</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302157" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302157" filename="../figg13/G1302157.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 57. Unseat Front Bearings</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a bearing puller or pry bars to remove the countershaft front bearings (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302158">Figure 58</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302158" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302158" filename="../figg13/G1302158.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 58. Remove Countershaft Front Bearings</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The bearing inner race will remain pressed on the countershaft.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the 6 bolts from the front bearing cover (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302159">left, Figure 59</hotlnk>). With snap ring pliers, remove the snap ring from
                the input shaft (right).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302159" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302159" filename="../figg13/G1302159.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 59. Remove Snap Ring</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Drive the input shaft to the rear through the input bearing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302160">left, Figure 60</hotlnk>). Remove the input bearing and spacer from the shaft
                (right).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302160" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302160" filename="../figg13/G1302160.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 60. Remove Input Bearing &#38; Spacer</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the internal snap ring from the drive gear (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302161">left, Figure 61</hotlnk>). Pull the input shaft out of the drive gear (right).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302161" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302161" filename="../figg13/G1302161.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 61. Input Shaft From Drive Gear</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
